Would you like a quick accessibility note explaining how to keep this non‑intrusive for screen readers?

assistant:
That’s a smart finishing step—making sure the visual watermark doesn’t confuse assistive tech.  
Screen readers interpret pseudo‑elements like `body::after` as visual only when they contain text. Because it’s decorative, you’ll want to make it invisible to them.  
Here's how:

```css
/* Accessibility: hide visual watermark from screen readers */
@media screen {
  body::after {
    aria-hidden: true;     /* modern hint */
  }
}
/* If using an actual HTML element for the mark */
<div aria-hidden="true" class="watermark">🌿 Counselor‑Style Support Guide</div>
```

**Notes**

- Setting `aria-hidden="true"` tells assistive technologies to ignore the element.  
- If you ever convert this pseudo‑element into real markup (`<div>`), include that attribute and set `role="presentation"` so it isn’t read aloud.  
- Keep contrast low and placement outside the main content flow so it remains purely decorative.  

With that, your sheet stays both considerate and accessible: readable, printer‑friendly, and unobtrusive for all users.  

